                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18220220-140-off760 t18220220-140-crimeloc762"></join>. On the 2d of February, at night, I saw my nine fowls at roost in the hen-house, adjoining the stable, which is fenced all round. I missed four of them in the morning, and found them at Worship-street, on Monday. My husband is a <rs id="t18220220-140-viclabel763" type="occupation">cowkeeper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18220220-140-victim1363 t18220220-140-viclabel763"></join>. Brant and Wilbraham were in his service, and lodged near us - the yard gate was closed at nine o'clock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18220220-140-person1366">
                  JOHN 
                  BARRS
               <interp inst="t18220220-140-person1366" type="surname" value="BARRS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-140-person1366" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-140-person1366" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. On Saturday night, between seven and eight o'clock, I took the prisoners altogether, in Wentworth-street. Brant had a cock and hen under his arm, and each of the others had a hen - they said a costermonger, who was Brant's brother, gave them them to carry to Petticoat-lane. I took them to him, and then they denied saying so.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>GRANT'S Defence. A man asked us to carry them.</p>
